land © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: variant of   Monnington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Monnington","meanings":["English: locative name from Monnington on Wye or Monnington Straddle in Vowchurch (both Herefs)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Mordington was born about 1236, in Mordington Mains, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the daughter of Peter de Mordington. She married Henry Haliburton before 1256. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1323, in Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 88."},"et":{"Abt 1236–1323":"umbes 1236–1323","1236–1323":"1236–1323","1232–1320":"1232–1320","–Male":"Surnud","1256–1337":"1256–1337","1205–1276":"1205–1276","1205":"1205","1337":"1337","1236":"1236","1323":"1323","before 1256":"enne 1256","1256":"1256","1320":"1320","1276":"1276","1232":"1232","Abt 1236":"umbes 1236","after 1276":"pärast 1276","after 1256":"pärast 1256","Haliburton, Berwick, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Halyburton, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Mordington Mains, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Mording